"(1)  \nMoonlight, pale as dust on a winter windowpane, clung to the iron bones of the High Line as evening settled over the city. Above the elevated rail, steel arches curved overhead, their shadows stretching across the black asphalt. The hum of distant traffic, the faint murmur of an audience settling into plush folding chairs, the scent of fresh popcorn mingling with the metallic tang of rain that had threatened all day. For Jackson, standing near the balcony rail with his hands clasped tightly behind his back, the grandeur and gloom of this place felt like a double-edged blade—beauty and decay entwined.\n\n(2)  \nHe watched the lights dim, and the hush fall like a shroud. Somewhere behind him, a stranger leaned in and whispered, “Do you often come to the theater after meetings?” without knowing who would hear. His mind drifted to the conference earlier that morning, to the table crowded with city officials, each voice competing for air, his own steady but hollow—words about budgets and the dying embers of the city’s stages. Jackson had discussed theater funding, not for applause but for answers, yet the room echoed with empty hopes, not solutions.  \n\n(3)  \nThe stage lights flickered to life. A curtain rose, revealing a set both opulent and hollow—gilded columns, glass domes that glittered but seemed fragile, as if they might shatter at any touch. On center stage, a solitary actor in a blood-red coat emerged, his face half-lit by a solitary spotlight. The music that rose was beautiful, but melancholy, a violin sighing an old tune. Jackson felt the ache of expectations—what the funding could have secured, what was lost, and what would soon be forgotten. The date hung in his mind: February 27, 2026, a year that promised closure but offered only silence.  \n\n(4)  \nThe performance moved forward in slow, inevitable steps. The actor’s gestures grew more desperate as the narrative unraveled, each line etched with longing but unresolved. The audience below was motionless, caught in their own grief, faces blurred in the soft light. Jackson closed his eyes, imagining the empty seats if his proposal had failed, the programs left unread, the actors without a stage to return to. He wanted to reach out, to help—but his voice was only a whisper in the swell of the performance, a voice drowned by the same indifference that had threatened to"